Minister Pandiarajan said that historical traces have been found in the 5th phase of excavations that will enhance Keezhadi&#39;s fame worldwide.
Jayakanthan, Minister of Kathir and Village Industries Board G. Baskaran, Minister of Tamil Official Language and Tamil Culture K. Pandiarajan visited and told reporters:
The Keezhadi Phase 5 excavation marks a turning point in the study of Sangam history in Tamil Nadu.
Keezhadi was a prosperous area from the 6th century BC to the 1st century AD.
This study focuses on urbanization along the banks of the Vaigai River based on currently available evidence.
Scientific chronology at the excavations at Keezhadi has determined that the Tamil-Brahmi period is 100 years older. This study reveals that Tamil Nadu was a literate society as early as the 6th century BC.
Furthermore, samples of 70 bone fragments unearthed through this study have been sent to Deccan College, a postgraduate and research institute, for scientific analysis.
These fossils were classified according to their characteristics during analysis, and the following species were identified: buffalo, buffalo, goat, wild boar, reindeer, and peacock.
This study suggests that animals such as cows, buffaloes, and goats support agriculture, and that some of the fossil specimens of animals such as reindeer, wild boar, and wild boar have been found to have fang marks, indicating that these animals are also used for food.
By the end of this analysis, the Sangam society, which was primarily agricultural, also took up animal husbandry.
Samples of bricks, limestone-based roof tiles and clay-based plaster of the well have been sent to the Vellore University of Technology for analysis.
Minerals such as silica, limestone, iron, aluminum, and magnesium are found in each of these studies.
To preserve such rare species, work is underway to establish a museum at a prime location at an estimated cost of Rs. 20 crores so that more Tamil scholars, students, and the general public can visit and benefit from the Keezhadi area.
Furthermore, the 5th phase of excavation work will be extended for two weeks and the work will continue.
Similarly, the state government will jointly carry out the 6th phase of excavation work at four locations next year, in collaboration with the central government, said Tamil Official Language and Tamil Culture Minister K. Pandiarajan.
Manamadurai MLA S. Nagarajan, former MP Senthilnathan, Assistant Director of Archaeological Department Jeevanantham, Conservator Aasaithambi, Thiruppuvanam Taluk Officer Raja and many others participated in the event.
