When Modi was the first Prime Minister, Tamil Nadu was in a situation where it was necessary to abandon the lotus and look for a way out.
After this, for the second time, that is, during the recently concluded MP elections, Amit Shah sternly stated, &quot;I don&#39;t know what you will do. The lotus should bloom in Tamil Nadu.&quot;
However, they were only able to win in the five constituencies they contested.
Even though the BJP is praised across the country, there is a wave of opposition in Tamil Nadu.
This is above all triple talaq, the Kashmir issue, Hindi imposition, and one nation, one language.
Because everything comes together like this, it is still visible in the sky.
That is why it is said that the BJP leadership is very strict with the Tamil Nadu BJP executives, and because of this, there has been such a problem that it has not even been possible to appoint a state leadership yet.
Although this is one sided, the BJP is planning to somehow entrench itself in Tamil Nadu by the upcoming assembly elections.
It seems that the BJP leadership has almost reached a conclusion through direct field reports and intelligence reports.
Accordingly, there is a prevailing perception among the people of the respective communities that both Dravidian parties, whether it is the AIADMK or the DMK, do not give sufficient importance to the Nadar ethnic people, the Vanniyar ethnic people, and the Devendra Kula Vellalar people.
It is also said that they are upset with the Dravidian parties for this.
The BJP has cunningly taken up this tactic and started implementing it.
They have decided to honor and give a position to their respective communities in a way that makes them proud or gives them importance.
The appointment of Tamilisai Soundararajan as the Governor of Telangana is one such example.
Similarly, it is said that the BJP government is also giving importance to Nadars in high positions in ISRO.
It is true that if the BJP acts in a way that honors each community, it will bring pride and happiness to the people of the respective communities.
Moreover, something that is not good for anything will only be good for the BJP in this caste politics.
At the same time, it is unclear whether these actions by the BJP will add fuel to the fire, as Tamil Nadu is already being torn apart by caste politics.
The truth is that if the fire of caste starts to flare up and burn, even the bud of the lotus that is now blooming a little in Tamil Nadu will be scorched and consumed by the same fire!
A laborer was murdered by a drunken man near Villupuram.
A laborer was brutally murdered by a young man with a knife in a clash near Valavanur, Villupuram.
Tensions arose as the assistant inspector who went to catch the criminal was also attacked with a knife.
Thanigairaj (28), son of Pichaikkaran, hails from Kengarampalayam Colony area near Valavanur near Villupuram.
Laborer.
Ayyanar (33), son of Kasinathan, is from the same area.
They have been involved in frequent drunken arguments and clashes in the area.
There are also cases against them at Valavanur police station.
In this situation, Aiyanar, who is in the business of selling fresh water, has a habit of drinking alcohol at night and occasionally threatening the public with a knife.
In this regard, on Saturday evening, after drinking alcohol, he came to the Kengarampalayam Colony area carrying a knife used to cut water lilies and threatening people on the road.
At that time, Aiyanar went to Thanigairaj&#39;s house due to a previous enmity and had an argument with him at home.
In the ensuing confrontation, Ilanir Seemu suddenly slashed Thanigairaju with a knife.
In this, Thanigairaj fell down in a pool of blood and died on the spot.
Following this, Ayyanar wandered the streets, chasing away the public with a knife.
Upon receiving the information, Valanur Assistant Police Inspector Manikandan and the police rushed to the spot and tried to arrest him.
At that time, Assistant Inspector Manikandan was injured by a knife attack, resulting in a cut on his hand.
He was immediately admitted to a private hospital and received treatment.
Following this, the police arrested Ayyanar and took him to the police station.
Upon receiving information about the incident, Villupuram DSP J. Shankar, Valavanur Police Inspector Nandagopal and the police rushed to the scene of the murder and conducted an investigation.
Police security was put in place after a murder incident in Kengarampalayam, a border area of Puducherry state, caused panic.
Based on the complaint, the Valavanur police have registered a murder case, arrested Ayyanar and are conducting an intensive investigation.
A road safety camp and awareness rally was organized by the New Prince Sri Bhavani Arts and Science College in Medavakkam, near Chennai, and the Chennai Metropolitan Traffic Police Department (Madivakkam Traffic Police Station).
M. Prabhakaran, Director of New Prince Sri Bhavani College of Arts and Science, welcomed everyone.
Senior Chief Minister V. Karunanidhi, Chief Minister V. Uma Devi, Deputy Chief Minister A. Mathiyapayas Bacheli and others were present.
The Road Safety Awareness Camp was inaugurated by L. Naveen Prasad, Vice President of New Prince Educational Groups.
Madipakkam Traffic Police Inspector Sivasankaran participated as the special guest and inaugurated the awareness rally by waving the flag, presenting a guidebook on road safety rules to the students and delivering a special speech.
Speaking at the time, he said that the need for road rules should start with students, because parents and this society depend on them.
Youth are the most affected by road accidents, and to prevent this, awareness programs like this should be conducted in schools and colleges.
Everyone should follow traffic rules not to get fined, but to save your own life.
Students are required to wear helmets when riding a two-wheeler and should never use cell phones while driving.
Vehicles should be operated only after properly learning the rules of the road.
Motorists should provide adequate cooperation to traffic police.
If every college administration continuously monitors the students&#39; adherence to road rules, it can save the precious lives of students.
The future of the country lies in the hands of the youth, and protecting such youth is an essential duty of the traffic police and the public.
Assistant Inspector Ravikumar, Head Constables Kandeepan, Srinivasan, Thiagarajan and others participated in the camp.
Today marks 42 years since the death of Professor Senaka Vibile.
Today marks 42 years since the passing of Professor Senaka Vibile, a pioneer of the National Pharmaceutical Policy.
He was mysteriously murdered on the island of Guyana.
He was the country&#39;s first professor in the field of medicine.
Professor Senaka Vibile served as the first Dean of the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Peradeniya.
He exposed issues related to the sale of medicines carried out by multinational companies in the country and was subjected to various pressures by these vendors.
The loss to the government from drugs imported into the country under various names amounts to crores of rupees.
Thus, he highlighted to the government the need for a national drug policy.
He worked to provide patients with 335 types of medicines at reasonable prices and with high quality.
Because of this act of his, he became the object of the zeal of multi-ethnic organizations.
The mystery of his death has not yet been revealed.
Prime Minister Narendra Modi did not utter a single word regarding the Jammu and Kashmir issue during his speech at the United Nations today.
The 74th session of the United Nations is currently underway.
Prime Minister Narendra Modi addressed the gathering on behalf of India today.
During his speech, he called on the world to unite against terrorism.
He also remembered the line sung by the Tamil poet Kaniyan Poonkundranar, &quot;Everywhere in the world, everyone sings.&quot;
Modi proudly stated that India is making a major contribution towards solving the problem of global warming, and that India&#39;s contribution to global warming is minimal, while the solution is more.
The Indian government is taking serious steps to make the country a plastic-free country.
He said that a massive health insurance scheme is being implemented in India.
You all, everywhere, listen. . Modi spoke a wonderful idea to the world in Tamil at the UN.
But nowhere in his speech did he mention anything related to the Jammu and Kashmir issue.
The reason for this is that the central government is firmly of the opinion that Jammu and Kashmir is an internal matter of India.
Political observers say that Modi deliberately refrained from speaking a single word on Jammu and Kashmir, as Pakistan wanted to internationalize the issue.
This has sent a message to the world that Kashmir is India&#39;s internal matter.
2,993 tribals have passed the literacy test held in Kerala.
An 85-year-old woman has also passed this exam.
According to the 2011 census, 93.91 percent of the population in Kerala was literate.
The Kerala state government is making efforts to make this 100 percent.
For this, a State Literacy Commission was set up.
This commission is conducting literacy classes and examinations in every district.
In particular, this commission is making serious efforts to provide literacy to tribals, fishermen, and migrant workers.
In this situation, literacy classes have been held for people in the tribal-dominated areas of Wayanad district since last February, and an exam was recently conducted.
The exam was of 100 marks; 30 marks were allocated for reading ability, 40 marks for writing ability, and 30 marks for mathematical knowledge.
It is mandatory to score 30 marks to pass this exam.
3,090 tribals from Wayanad district participated in this exam.
The Literacy Commission reported that 2,993 of them passed.
One of them is an 85-year-old woman.
Director of School Education S. Kannappan has ordered to provide textbooks and notebooks for the second semester to students studying in 27 government and government-aided schools on Oct. 3.
In this regard, he sent a circular to all District Principal Education Officers and District Education Officers on Wednesday:
Free notebooks have been provided to government and government-aided schools in all districts through TNPL.
Similarly, free textbooks for the second semester have been sent through the Tamil Nadu Textbook Corporation.
All District Primary Education Officers should provide textbooks and notebooks to all government and government aided schools in their districts by Sept. 30.
Furthermore, it states that all principals should be instructed to provide free textbooks and notebooks for the second semester on the first day students return to school after the quarterly vacation.
